c. Suetonius employs an extramdinary number of technical phrases and expressions :

qui . . perduellionis diem diceret, Jul. 12; cum . . . denuntiaret delaturum se nomen eius, Jul. 90. 3; Recensum populi. . . uicatim. . . ‘eyit, Jul. 41. 3; inter officia prosequentium fascesque lictorum, Jul. 71; in secundis heredibus, Jul. 83. 2; divisores operasque campestres, Any. 3.1; reosque caedis absentis deferre statuit, Any. 10.1; publicum . . . et translatiuum ius, Auy. 10. 2; Cumque. . uliam capi oporteret ombi- rentoue multi nefilias in sortem darent, Auy. 31. 9,· Ne qnod auam male- ficium neyotiumae inpunitate vel mora elaberetur, Any. 32. 2; Affuit et clientibus. . . qui postulabatur iniuriarum, Auy. 56. 4.

· (l. Of about one hundred words borrowed from the Greek that occur in these two Lives the following are a few of the most unusual in their Latinized spelling, several of these are exceedingly rare:

aretaloyos, Any. 74; Autoyrapha, Auo. 71. 2 ; cacozelos, Auy. 86. 2 ; carcinomata, Auy. 65. 4; roacare, Auy. 94. 7 ; collybo, ¹Any. 4.2 (quo- tation); conchyliatae, Jul. 43.1; disticho, Jul. 51; perenaeos, Auy. 71.2 (quotation); locham‘zare, Any. 87.2 (quotation); myrobrechis, Auy. 86.2 (quotation) ; naumachiam, Jul. 99. l ; Orthoyraphlam, Auy. 88; phonasco, Any. 84.2; Pyrrichum, Jul. 39.1; technyphion, Auy. 72. 2; thalameyo, Jul. 52. 1; thema, Auy. 94.12; tympanizante, Auy. 68 ; xysticorum, Auy. 45. 4 ; cyulis, Auy. 72. 3.

Some of these words would more properly be printed in Greek characters, as are εὐθανασίαν (Any. 99. 2) and others: especially, yerontihos, myrobrechis, technyphion.
